// AI Hackathon Orientation - Question Bank (GIFT)

::AHO01_HackathonDefinition::
An AI hackathon is best described as:
{
=A short, time-boxed event where teams build or improve a practical AI solution
~A mandatory production release with no room for experimentation
~A certification exam for software engineers only
~A vendor demo with no team participation
}

::AHO02_PrimaryOutcome::
What is the most common outcome of an AI hackathon?
{
=A working prototype that proves an idea and shows value
~A fully governed enterprise platform ready for all users
~A complete replacement for every existing business process
~A guarantee that no further development will be needed
}

::AHO03_NotProduction::
Which statement is most accurate?
{
=Hackathons usually aim to test and demonstrate ideas quickly, not finish full production delivery
~Hackathons should avoid all experimentation
~Hackathons are only useful after a product is already complete
~Hackathons remove the need for business input
}

::AHO04_WhyOrganizationsRunThem::
Why do organizations run AI hackathons?
{
=To explore useful ideas quickly, learn fast, and connect business needs to technical prototypes
~To prevent teams from working together
~To replace every project with a two-day event
~To avoid making decisions after the event
}

::AHO05_BusinessRole::
What is a key contribution from business-focused departments during a hackathon?
{
=They provide process knowledge, customer context, constraints, and success criteria
~They only observe and should not influence the solution
~They mainly choose the font and slide colors
~They are responsible for writing every line of code themselves
}

::AHO06_WeakOutcome::
Which result is a weak hackathon outcome?
{
=A technically interesting demo with no clear user problem or business value
~A prototype that runs and is tied to a real need
~A solution with a clear explanation of who benefits
~A demo that shows what the team learned
}

::AHO07_DayOneFocus::
What is a likely focus on day 1 of the hackathon?
{
=Understanding the challenge, setting up the environment, and getting the starter solution running
~Finalizing enterprise procurement paperwork
~Replacing all legacy systems immediately
~Skipping the setup and going straight to production launch
}

::AHO08_DayTwoFocus::
What is a likely focus on day 2 of the hackathon?
{
=Refining the prototype, testing it, and preparing a short explanation or demo
~Ignoring the business problem and adding unrelated features
~Deleting the working prototype to start over from zero
~Avoiding all testing to save time
}

::AHO09_BestMindset::
What mindset is most helpful in an AI hackathon?
{
=Build something small that works and connects clearly to the problem being solved
~Try to make the broadest possible system, even if nothing works
~Avoid asking what the user problem is
~Treat the event like a solo competition only for technical specialists
}

::AHO10_TechAndBusiness::
Why do the best hackathon teams combine technical and business participants?
{
=Technical participants can build the solution, while business participants help ensure it solves the right problem
~Because business participants should prevent any technology work
~Because technical participants should avoid user problems
~Because the team should separate business value from the prototype
}
